  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering carries serious criminal penalties. Here are the key points:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in the transaction\n\n2. Specific Legal Provisions:\n- Prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957\n- Penalties depend on specific circumstances of the offense\n- Can involve both criminal and civil penalties\n\n3. Factors Affecting Penalties:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Intent of the offender\n- Whether transaction involved proceeds from specific criminal activities\n- Prior criminal history\n\n4. Additional Consequences:\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty obtaining future employment\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n5. Aggravating Factors:\n- Laundering funds related to specific crimes like drug trafficking\n- Involvement in organized criminal enterprises\n- International money laundering schemes\n\nThese penalties represent general federal guidelines. Specific circumstances can significantly impact the actual legal consequences.\n\nPlease note: This information is for general educational purposes and should not be considered specific legal advice. Consulting a qualified attorney is recommended for precise legal guidance.",
